awd_titl_txt: MRI: Acquisition of a Single Crystal X-ray Diffractometer for Research and Education at an HBCU
awd_abstract_narration:
This award to Hampton University is supported by the Major Research Instrumentation and the Chemistry Research Instrumentation programs to support research by Oluwatoyin Asojo and colleagues Kesete Ghebreyessus, Peter Njoki and Rupak Dua. This institution is acquiring a single crystal X-ray difffractometer (SCXRD). In general, an X-ray diffractometer allows accurate and precise measurements of the full three-dimensional structure of a molecule, including bond distances and angles, and provides accurate information about the spatial arrangement of a molecule relative to neighboring molecules. The studies described here impact many areas, including organic and inorganic chemistry, materials chemistry, geology and biochemistry. This instrument is an integral part of teaching as well as research and research training of undergraduate students in chemistry and biochemistry at this Historically Black College and University (HBCU) as well as Old Dominion University. The instrumentation provides direct research experience for students in a variety of courses distributed in various departments. Seminars on structural science engage additional regional users and other neighboring universities. 

The award of the X-ray diffractometer is aimed at enhancing research and education at all levels. The science enabled by this instrument provides relevant societal benefits by associating protein structures and the chemistry of life and by developing ruthenium(II)-arene complexes appended with hemilabile photoswitchable ligands. The instrumentation is also used for studying, designing and fabricating non-noble copper-based materials for electrocatalytic reduction of carbon dioxide and for studies employing bioengeneering materials for use in musculoskeletal disorders. The diffractometer is also used to carry out photocatalytic and mechanistic studies of clusters having a core composed of four cobalt and four oxygen atoms (Co4O4).

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

PROJECT OUTCOME REPORT

Intellectual Merit

The Rigaku Xtalab synergy single crystal X-ray diffractometer instrument acquired with funds provided by the NSF Major Research Instrumentation grant (Award # 2117763) was successfully installed. Having access to the X-ray diffractometer system have enhanced faculty research in the areas of protein chemistry, inorganic chemistry, nanoscale materials and solid state materials. The instrument has allowed for the investigation of structure-property relationships in protein structures towards the development of novel antimalarial therapies and the nature of the self-assembly process of soft metallogel materials. The nature of the prominent intermolecular forces (hydrogen-bonding, p-p stacking and electrostatic) contributing to the self-assembly processes of the gels were probed as function of subtle changes on the molecular structures of the ligands used for the gelation, yielding useful insights into futures design of nanoscale soft metallogel materials with applications in sensors, actuators and environmental remediation. Data acquired using this instrument has been presented by undergraduate and graduate students in regional and local conferences.

PROJECT OUTCOME REPORT


Intellectual Merit


The Rigaku Xtalab synergy single crystal X-ray diffractometer instrument acquired with funds provided by the NSF Major Research Instrumentation grant (Award # 2117763) was successfully installed. Having access to the X-ray diffractometer system have enhanced faculty research in the areas of protein chemistry, inorganic chemistry, nanoscale materials and solid state materials. The instrument has allowed for the investigation of structure-property relationships in protein structures towards the development of novel antimalarial therapies and the nature of the self-assembly process of soft metallogel materials. The nature of the prominent intermolecular forces (hydrogen-bonding, p-p stacking and electrostatic) contributing to the self-assembly processes of the gels were probed as function of subtle changes on the molecular structures of the ligands used for the gelation, yielding useful insights into futures design of nanoscale soft metallogel materials with applications in sensors, actuators and environmental remediation. Data acquired using this instrument has been presented by undergraduate and graduate students in regional and local conferences.








Broader Impact


The X-ray diffractometer allowed us to introduce undergraduate and graduate students from underrepresented minorities to modern analytical tools used in structural analysis in various scientific disciplines. Since the instrument has been fully operational, 6 faculty members that include 3 newly hired assistant professors have been trained in crystal mounting, data acquisition, processing and general operation of the X-ray instrument. Access to the new instrument also enabled to introduce undergraduate students to the importance of X-ray crystallography in structural analysis in the traditional laboratory courses. Particularly, the new instrument was utilized in enhancing the educational activities of the course-based undergraduate research experience (CUREs) general chemistry laboratory course taken by diverse group of chemistry and biochemistry majors and non-majors. Students in this laboratory course prepared Artists Paint. X-ray powder diffraction patterns of these materials have been characterized with the help of the instrument acquired through the MRI grant and the results were discussed in the laboratory classroom. Exposure of these students to a modern instruments early in their training has the potential to enhance participation in undergraduate research and increase their persistence in STEM degree programs. Additionally, the instrument has been used to complete a Masters Thesis, and to train a postdoctoral research fellow from engineering and physics. The benefits of the new instrument will be expanded into more introductory and advanced level courses to provide hands-on-training to chemistry and biochemistry majors to stimulate their laboratory and scientific commutations skills. The department of chemistry and biochemistry has recently added three new assistant professor faculty specializing in analytical, inorganic chemistry and biochemistry all of which will clearly benefit with the availability of the new X-ray crystallography analysis facility. The new X-ray instrument was also used during high school and admitted students days at the University to show case prospective students the type of modern analytical tolls we have, which enhances recruitment of new students.
